William Shakespeare’s play “Julius Caesar” explored the idea that there are consequences for envy and ambition through the characters of Lassies and Caesar. Lassies, at the start of the play, found the conspiracy because of his envy for Caesar’s position rather than fear that Caesar will create a dictatorship. When convincing Brutus to join his cause, Lassies says, “And this man is now become a god, and Lassies is a wretched creature and must bend his body if Caesar carelessly but nod on him,” (1.2.122 - 125). His indicates that Lassies feels that he should be equal to Caesar rather than having to bow down to him. His resent towards Caesar is eventually what leads to his downfall, as he ends up going through with the assassination and then killing himself as he watches his army lose. Additionally, previous passages suggest that Lassies and Caesar have been equals in the past and have watched each other grow. However, Caesar has moved ahead of Lassies due to his ambition and his supposed possession with power. The conspirators, picking up on this, assume that Caesar’s motives and methods will change as he acquires more power and feel that by getting rid of him, they can take some for themselves.

The passage that intrigues me most was the repeating of the word "soundness" throughout paragraph 39 on page 454. In paragraph 37, Winston describes the true reason that the villagers attacked her aunt: "to show [her aunt] a personal, physical representation of the break she made in the 'soundness'" (Winston para. 37). His implies that when Winston describes "soundness" it represents formality, traditions, and the status que. His is further emphasized in paragraph 39 as the "talismans" warning the family to keep with tradition are all described as "round": the moon cakes, doorways, "tables of graduated size", windows, rice bowls, etc. But this soundness protecting the village from the unknown was defeated by one adulterous woman. The villagers attacked not because they thought adultery was a sin, nor even because the baby would use up precious resources. They attacked because they were afraid that the unnamed aunt would shatter their perceptions of reality and invite others to do the same. Denying tradition also meant denying accidents, forcing the people to accept fault for their own mistakes instead of blaming it on gods or the stars. Winston uses the repetition of the word “round” and variations thereon to draw attention to the village’s stubborn refusal to accept change and emphasize the villagers’ desire to maintain the “curling of events” that had continued for hundreds of years.

Of. I think that the meaning of this essay to me is twofold: the culture of silence/measure and choosing between one’s culture and what is “right”. Winston’s essay first establishes the former, as it describes the aunt’s story and how the family is forced to stay quiet and forget that it happens because of their culture. I think this is a very common thing that you see with a lot of families, as there are certain things that will never leave the house and never be talked about ever again. It’s generally accepted, at least by my family and that of my friends, that any argument that happens in the house doesn’t leave it because that imparts peoples’ impression of us. In terms of what the latter means to me, I think that at some level everyone has to make that choice, whether they will continue to walk the path of “purity” as dictated by their culture or whether they will make the decision their gut tells them is right. In the first portion of his letter, Gandhi uses repetition and fiction to portray himself as a servant of the British and show that he is working for the greater good of both India and Britain. Gandhi writes, “For my ambition is no less than to convert the British people through non-violence...” (9-11). Gandhi uses the word “convert” because his aim isn’t to hurt the British, but rather make them see their past wrongs. Although “convert” already implies that he is working for the common good, Gandhi explicitly spells out that he aims to do this through non-violence, further enforcing the idea that he has no intention of causing harm to the British. His idea is reiterated as Gandhi notes how, “I have served them up to 1919, blandly. But when my eyes are opened and I conceived non-cooperation, my object still was to serve them” (16 – 18). The repetition of the word “serve” makes it clear that he wishes to work with the British empire to change their ways. Since the consolation of the word ‘serve’ is inherently respectful, it is further clear that Gandhi is working to better both Britain and India. Therefore, in the first section of the letter, Gandhi makes clear his interest for the betterment of both India and Britain.
